NOTES_NUMBERS_17_20 = {
    17: {
        8: 'THE BUDDING ROD: A dead stick comes to life overnight -- buds, blossoms, and ripe almonds simultaneously. This is resurrection in miniature. God vindicates Aaron\'s priesthood not through argument but through life from death. CHRIST TYPOLOGY: The dead wood that blooms is a picture of the cross that becomes the tree of life. Christ\'s resurrection validates His priesthood: \'You are a priest forever, according to the order of Melchizedek\' (Heb 5:6). The almond (shaqed) puns on shaqad (\'to watch, to be vigilant\') -- God watches over His word to perform it (Jer 1:11-12).',
        10: 'THE ROD PRESERVED: Aaron\'s rod is placed inside the ark alongside the tablets of the law and the jar of manna (Heb 9:4). Three witnesses inside God\'s throne: the law (God\'s word), the manna (God\'s provision), and the rod (God\'s chosen priesthood). All three point to Christ: He is the Word made flesh, the Bread of Life, and the eternal High Priest.',
        12: 'THE PEOPLE\'S TERROR: \'We perish, we are dying, we are all dying!\' -- three escalating expressions of dread. The people finally understand the danger of God\'s holiness. After Korah\'s earth-swallowing, the plague, and the budding rod, they grasp that approaching God without authorized mediation is fatal. This terror creates the context for chapter 18, which answers: how can sinful people live near a holy God? Through appointed priests.',
    },
    18: {
        7: 'PRIESTHOOD AS GIFT: \'I am giving you the priesthood as a bestowed service\' -- the priesthood is not a right seized (as Korah attempted) but a gift given. The Hebrew mattanah avodah (\'a gift of service\') combines privilege and duty. Priesthood is both honor and burden.',
        19: 'COVENANT OF SALT: An \'everlasting covenant of salt\' -- salt preserves and does not decay. A salt covenant is permanent and irrevocable (cf. 2 Chr 13:5). The priestly provisions are as permanent as the covenant itself. CHRIST: The Levitical priesthood was temporary (Heb 7:11-12), but what it pointed to -- Christ\'s eternal priesthood -- is truly a covenant of salt that never expires.',
        20: 'I AM YOUR PORTION: God Himself is the Levites\' inheritance. While other tribes receive land, the Levites receive God. This is the highest theology of ministry: the minister\'s reward is not territory or wealth but the presence of God. Psalm 73:25-26: \'Whom have I in heaven but You? And besides You I desire nothing on earth... God is the strength of my heart and my portion forever.\' CHRIST: Every believer is now a priest (1 Pet 2:9) whose inheritance is God Himself.',
    },
    19: {
        2: 'THE RED HEIFER: One of the most mysterious rituals in all of Scripture. The rabbis said that even Solomon, the wisest man, could not understand it (Midrash Rabbah). A perfectly red, unblemished cow that has never worn a yoke -- burned entirely outside the camp, its ashes mixed with water for purification from corpse contamination. PARADOX: The heifer purifies the unclean, but everyone who handles it becomes unclean. Purity comes through contact with what absorbs impurity.',
        6: 'CEDAR, HYSSOP, SCARLET: The same three elements used in the cleansing of a leper (Lev 14:4-6). Cedar (the tallest tree), hyssop (the lowest plant), scarlet (the color of blood/sin) -- from the greatest to the least, all is consumed in the purifying fire. CHRIST TYPOLOGY: Hebrews 9:13-14: \'If the blood of goats and bulls and the ashes of a heifer sprinkling those who have been defiled sanctify for the cleansing of the flesh, how much more will the blood of Christ, who through the eternal Spirit offered Himself without blemish to God, cleanse your conscience from dead works?\' The red heifer = Christ. Unblemished, never under a yoke (free from sin\'s bondage), slain outside the camp (Heb 13:11-12: \'Jesus also suffered outside the gate\'), purifying those contaminated by death.',
        12: 'THIRD AND SEVENTH DAY: Purification on the third day and the seventh day. CHRIST: Christ rose on the third day (1 Cor 15:4) and will consummate all things at the seventh -- the Sabbath rest. The two-stage purification mirrors the already/not-yet of salvation.',
    },
    20: {
        1: 'MIRIAM\'S DEATH: A single verse for the death of a prophetess. Miriam, who led the women in song at the Red Sea (Exod 15:20-21), who watched over baby Moses in the Nile (Exod 2:4), dies quietly at Kadesh. The Talmud (Ta\'anit 9a) associates her death with the drying up of the water supply -- Miriam\'s well. The first of the three wilderness leaders (Miriam, Aaron, Moses) now falls.',
        8: 'SPEAK TO THE ROCK: God says \'speak.\' At the first Meribah (Exod 17:6), God told Moses to \'strike.\' This time the command is different. Grace requires only a word, not a blow. The rock only needed to be struck once -- just as Christ was crucified once for all (Heb 9:28; 10:10).',
        11: 'MOSES\' SIN: Moses strikes the rock twice instead of speaking to it. He says \'shall WE bring forth water\' -- taking credit that belongs to God. He acts in anger rather than faith. The severity of the punishment (exclusion from the land) reflects the principle that greater privilege brings greater accountability. Moses was \'faithful in all God\'s house\' (12:7); this failure at the threshold of the land is devastating precisely because of who he is. CHRIST TYPOLOGY: The rock is Christ (1 Cor 10:4). Christ was struck once at the cross. After the resurrection, we approach Him by speaking (prayer), not by striking. Moses\' error was re-striking what God had already provided through one sufficient blow.',
        12: 'BELIEVED ME / TREAT ME AS HOLY: The two charges -- unbelief and failure to sanctify God -- are one sin. Moses did not trust God\'s word (speak vs. strike) and therefore did not display God\'s holiness to the people. Leaders\' public sins have public consequences.',
        21: 'EDOM\'S REFUSAL: Edom = Esau\'s descendants. Israel and Edom are brothers (Jacob and Esau), yet Edom refuses passage. The ancient hostility continues. Obadiah 1:10-14 prophesies Edom\'s judgment for violence against his brother.',
        26: 'TRANSFER OF PRIESTHOOD: The garments are the office. When Aaron\'s robes are placed on Eleazar, the priesthood passes to the next generation. Aaron dies stripped of the symbols of his ministry -- he returns to God as a man, not as a priest. The office outlives the man. CHRIST: The Levitical priesthood required succession because priests died (Heb 7:23). Christ\'s priesthood needs no successor: \'He holds His priesthood permanently, because He continues forever\' (Heb 7:24).',
        28: 'AARON\'S DEATH: Aaron dies on Mount Hor, within sight of the Promised Land but unable to enter. Like Moses, the leader who brought Israel through the wilderness falls short of the goal. The generation of the Exodus is passing away. Thirty days of mourning -- the same period later given for Moses (Deut 34:8).',
    },
}
